Abstract

This paper proposes an alternative hypothesis for the evolution of the Earth-Moon system. The core claim is as follows: The main body of the present-day Moon is a super-comet nucleus (diameter ~4000–5000 km, density ~1000–1500 kg/m³) that was tidally captured by the Earth during the Late Pleistocene (approximately 30,000 years ago). During the capture process, it underwent tidal fragmentation at the Roche limit, producing a swarm of fragments that sequentially impacted the near side of the main nucleus over subsequent orbital cycles, forming the major lunar mare basins. The main nucleus subsequently converged with Earth’s original ancient satellite (diameter ~1000–2000 km) at low velocity through orbital resonance modulation — both bodies were locked within Earth’s gravitational well, their orbital period ratio was close to an integer, and their rendezvous was an inevitable outcome under gravitational laws. They ultimately completed a “soft merger” at an extremely low relative velocity. The merged body’s extremely thick ice shell underwent large-scale sublimation driven by solar radiation at low orbit and residual internal heat. The mass loss (on the order of ~10²² kg) drove orbital migration via conservation of angular momentum, pushing the Moon from an orbital distance of approximately 200,000–300,000 km to about 380,000 km. This constitutes the physical reality behind the myth of the “separation of heaven and earth.”

The unique starting point of this model is the decoding of the “cognitive encoding” of global creation myths. Using the method of visual fingerprint exclusion for candidate catastrophe models, it is demonstrated that only a super-comet nucleus making an extremely close flyby near the Roche limit can simultaneously produce the four visual features repeatedly recorded in mythology: an all-encompassing canopy dome, a vertical light pillar, sequential falling, and a multicolored sky curtain. Mythological data serve as a mandatory constraint for screening physical models.

This model independently explains the Moon’s hemispheric dichotomy, the concentration of maria on the near side with no central peaks, the coexistence of ancient mare basalt ages (3.3–3.8 Ga) with young surface structures, the compositional similarities between Earth and Moon, the fossil record of Earth’s day length, and the archaeological rupture in celestial worship from the Paleolithic to the Neolithic. It also proposes falsifiable testable predictions.

