1.3 Visual Fingerprint Exclusion of Candidate Catastrophe Models — Myth as a Physical Filter

This model’s choice of an “extreme close flyby of a super-comet” as the physical prototype for global creation myths stems not from theoretical preference, but from mandatory visual constraints within the mythological data itself.

1.3.1 The Four Visual Features of Myth — Phenomenological Constraints

A systematic review of visual descriptions in global creation myths yields four common features transcending cultural differences:

Feature 1: All-Encompassing Canopy Dome (“Chaos Like a Chicken’s Egg”)
The myths describe not a distant point of light, but a celestial phenomenon that covered the entire field of view and was enveloping. San Wu Liji records that before Pangu separated heaven and earth, “Heaven and earth were in chaos like a chicken’s egg”; the Biblical Genesis mentions “darkness upon the face of the deep”; Popol Vuh states “only the sky and the sea existed.” This demands a catastrophic celestial body with an extremely large angular diameter (>10°), occupying a vast area from horizon to zenith.

Feature 2: Vertical Light Pillar (“Heavenly Pillar”)
Imagery of a “Heavenly Pillar” or “Axis Mundi” exists in multiple civilizations’ myths. Huainanzi·Tianwen Xun mentions “The Heavenly Pillar broke, the earthly cord snapped”; in Greek mythology, Atlas holds up the sky with his shoulders, and Uranus is forcibly separated from Gaia after being castrated by Cronus; in Norse mythology, Ymir’s bones support the sky. This requires a light source with clear directional extension, stretching from near the ground to high altitude.

Feature 3: Sequential Falling (“Shooting the Suns”)
The multiple suns in myth do not vanish simultaneously but are shot down one by one. Huainanzi·Benjing Xun records: “During Yao’s time, ten suns came out together... Yao sent Yi to shoot the nine suns”; in the Indian Rigveda, Indra “kills Vritra” and releases the floods; in Maya myth, a rabbit scratches the Moon goddess, leaving dark marks on the Moon. This requires the existence of multiple independent luminous bodies in the sky that vanish one after another within an observable time window.

Feature 4: Multicolored Sky Curtain (“Mending the Sky with Five-Colored Stones”)
The discoloration of the sky is described as “five-colored” rather than a uniform grey. Huainanzi·Lanming Xun records “Nüwa smelted five-colored stones to mend the blue sky”; Greek mythology has Iris, the rainbow goddess; Norse mythology describes the “sky burning” at Ragnarök. This requires material entering the atmosphere to excite multi-wavelength visible light emission.

