3. Celestial Mechanics Model

3.1 Initial Condition: The Ancient Moon (Working Hypothesis)

This model proposes a working hypothesis: Earth originally possessed a rocky satellite (the Ancient Moon) with a diameter of approximately 1000–2000 km, mass on the order of 10²¹–10²² kg, and an orbital radius of roughly 100,000–300,000 km.

Supporting Arguments (Non-conclusive evidence):

Mars has two small moons while Earth has none — one of the most natural explanations is that Earth had one but it was merged or destroyed in a recent event.
Physical requirement of tidal braking: The fossil record indicates that approximately 620 million years ago, Earth's day length was 21.9±0.4 hours (Williams, 2000). An ancient moon at an orbit of 100,000–300,000 km with mass (10²¹–10²² kg) is sufficient to provide cumulative tidal dissipation over billions of years comparable to that of the present Moon (see Appendix A1 for detailed analysis).
Vesta (diameter 525 km) is fully differentiated, proving that large protoplanetary bodies existed in the early solar system. An ancient moon (1000–2000 km) forming and persisting in early Earth orbit is not impossible dynamically or thermally.
Candid admission: There is currently no direct observational evidence for the existence of the Ancient Moon; this is the most critical testable working hypothesis of this model. If future sampling of the lunar farside discovers rocks with Earth-identical isotopic signatures formed >4.0 Ga, the hypothesis is confirmed; if farside and nearside are both found to be of cometary composition, the hypothesis is falsified.

Visual prominence of the Ancient Moon: The ancient moon’s apparent diameter was only 0.15°–0.3° (depending on its orbit and size), having low visual salience, consistent with the rarity of explicit large satellite depictions in Upper Paleolithic cave art — human ancestors lived for hundreds of thousands of years in a state of “no prominent moon.”

