Important Clarification: Radioisotope ages of mare basalts (e.g., ⁴⁰Ar-³⁹Ar method) record the magmatic crystallization age — i.e., the time when the basalt lava flow cooled through the closure temperature. The ages of ~3.3–3.8 Ga from Apollo samples are firmly established magmatic activity ages.

This Model’s Interpretation — Two-Layer Age Model:
The formation of the mare basins (~30,000 years ago) and the filling by mare basalts (~3.3–3.8 Ga) are two independent events:

Ancient Basalt Substrate (3.3–3.8 Ga): The Ancient Moon (Earth’s original satellite) underwent internal magmatic activity billions of years ago, forming a basaltic crust. This corresponds to the measured ages of Apollo samples.
Young Impact Event (~30,000 years ago): When cometary fragments impacted the main nucleus, the target was first a ~1000 km thick ice layer and loose covering. By the time the shock wave reached the basalt substrate, its energy had decayed far below the rock melting threshold. The impact merely stripped the covering, exposing the ancient substrate, but did not reset its isotopic clock.
Shallow Surface Melting: The instantaneous high-temperature melting generated by the impacts only existed in a shallow surface layer (millimeter to meter scale) of ice-dust mixture. If preserved to this day, this material should yield ages of ~30,000 years — this is a core testable prediction of this model.
Falsification Condition: If future findings reveal large-volume (>1 m scale) ~30,000-year-old melt flows at the bottom of mare basins, or confirm that existing ~3.3–3.8 Ga basalt samples are all of impact melt origin rather than magmatic crystallization, this model would be invalidated.

3.5 Phase 3: Orbital Modulation — The “Inevitable Rendezvous” of Merger (Core Addition)

